{
  "A grayscale image of size m x n is naturally represented as:": "",
  "A scalar value": "",
  "A single vector of length m + n": "",
  "A complex number": "",
  "An m x n matrix of pixel intensity values": "",
  "A grayscale image is an m x n matrix where each entry represents the pixel intensity (typically 0-255 for 8-bit images). This matrix representation enables linear algebra operations for image processing.": "",
  "Image compression using SVD approximates an m x n image matrix A as A_k = U_k S_k V_k^T. If m = n = 500 and k = 20, how many values need to be stored?": "",
  "500": "",
  "250,000": "",
  "10,000": "",
  "20,020": "",
  "Store U_k (500x20 = 10,000) + S_k (20 values) + V_k (500x20 = 10,000) = 20,020 values instead of 250,000. This gives about 12.5:1 compression.": "",
  "In image filtering, convolution with a 3x3 kernel can be expressed as multiplication by which type of matrix?": "",
  "An orthogonal matrix": "",
  "A Toeplitz (block-Toeplitz) matrix": "",
  "A diagonal matrix": "",
  "A Hermitian matrix": "",
  "2D image convolution can be expressed as multiplication by a block-Toeplitz matrix with Toeplitz blocks. The kernel values appear shifted along diagonals, reflecting the translation-invariant nature of convolution.": "",
  "The Gaussian blur filter uses a kernel that approximates a Gaussian function. The 1D Gaussian kernel [1, 2, 1]/4 can be applied as a separable filter. What does 'separable' mean?": "",
  "The filter can be applied to each color channel independently": "",
  "The filter can be separated into real and imaginary parts": "",
  "The 2D kernel can be written as the outer product of two 1D kernels": "",
  "The filter produces no side effects": "",
  "A separable 2D filter K = h * h^T (outer product of 1D filters). Instead of convolving with the full m x n kernel (mn operations per pixel), you apply two 1D convolutions (m + n operations), dramatically reducing computation.": "",
  "The Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) of an image converts it from the spatial domain to the:": "",
  "Eigenvalue domain": "",
  "Time domain": "",
  "Frequency domain": "",
  "Color domain": "",
  "The 2D DFT decomposes an image into a sum of sinusoidal patterns of different frequencies, orientations, and phases. This frequency-domain representation is useful for filtering, compression, and analysis.": "",
  "In JPEG compression, images are divided into 8x8 blocks and transformed using the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT). The DCT matrix C for an 8x8 block is what type of matrix?": "",
  "Diagonal": "",
  "Orthogonal": "",
  "Singular": "",
  "Nilpotent": "",
  "The DCT matrix C is orthogonal (C^T C = I), meaning the transform is invertible and norm-preserving. The DCT is applied as CXC^T for each 8x8 block X, transforming to a frequency representation.": "",
  "Edge detection using the Sobel operator computes horizontal and vertical gradients. The Sobel horizontal kernel is [[-1,0,1],[-2,0,2],[-1,0,1]]. This kernel is separable as an outer product of which two vectors?": "",
  "It is not separable": "",
  "[1, 2, 1]^T and [-1, 0, 1]": "",
  "[1, 1, 1]^T and [-1, 0, 1]": "",
  "[1, 0, -1]^T and [1, 2, 1]": "",
  "[1,2,1]^T * [-1,0,1] = [[-1,0,1],[-2,0,2],[-1,0,1]], which is the Sobel horizontal kernel. The vertical smoothing [1,2,1] reduces noise while [-1,0,1] detects horizontal edges.": "",
  "A color image (RGB) with resolution m x n is represented as:": "",
  "A 3x3 matrix": "",
  "A vector of length 3mn": "",
  "Three m x n matrices (one per color channel)": "",
  "A single m x n matrix": "",
  "An RGB color image is represented as three separate m x n matrices for the Red, Green, and Blue channels. SVD or other matrix operations can be applied to each channel independently or jointly.": "",
  "In image denoising using SVD, noisy pixel values primarily affect which singular values?": "",
  "The largest singular values": "",
  "The smallest singular values": "",
  "All singular values equally": "",
  "Only the middle singular values": "",
  "Random noise contributes primarily to the smaller singular values because noise lacks the structured patterns captured by the dominant components. Truncating small singular values effectively removes noise.": "",
  "The eigenfaces approach to face recognition uses PCA on a set of face images. If there are 100 training images each of size 64x64, the eigenfaces are eigenvectors of which matrix?": "",
  "The 64 x 64 average face image": "",
  "Each individual face image matrix": "",
  "The 4096 x 4096 covariance matrix of the vectorized images": "",
  "The 100 x 100 identity matrix": "",
  "Each 64x64 image is vectorized to length 4096. The covariance matrix is 4096x4096, and its eigenvectors (eigenfaces) capture the principal variations. In practice, the smaller 100x100 matrix X^T X is used instead.": "",
  "What does 'image convolution' mean in linear algebra terms?": "",
  "Finding the eigenvalues of the image, particularly regarding expressed when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "A linear operation that applies a small matrix (kernel) to each local neighborhood of pixels, equivalent to matrix multiplication by a structured sparse matrix": "",
  "Computing the determinant of the image matrix, particularly regarding sums under normal circumstances": "",
  "Rotating an image by 90 degrees, particularly regarding position under normal circumstances": "",
  "Image convolution slides a kernel (small weight matrix) over the image, computing weighted sums at each position. This linear operation can be expressed as multiplication by a large sparse Toeplitz matrix.": "",
  "What is an 'image kernel' (filter)?": "",
  "The center pixel of an image": "",
  "The boundary of an image": "",
  "The null space of the image matrix": "",
  "A small matrix of weights applied to local pixel neighborhoods during convolution": "",
  "An image kernel is a small matrix (typically 3x3 or 5x5) whose entries are weights. Different kernels achieve different effects: blurring, sharpening, edge detection, embossing, etc.": "",
  "What does the 'Discrete Cosine Transform' (DCT) do to an image block?": "",
  "Transforms spatial pixel values into frequency coefficients using cosine basis functions": "",
  "Compresses the image by removing pixels": "",
  "Converts the image from RGB to grayscale": "",
  "Rotates the image block by a fixed angle": "",
  "The DCT represents an image block as a weighted sum of cosine basis functions of increasing frequency. Low-frequency coefficients capture smooth variations while high-frequency ones capture sharp details and noise.": "",
  "What is 'image sharpening' in terms of matrix operations?": "",
  "Multiplying all pixel values by 2, particularly regarding sharpening in most standard conditions": "",
  "Reducing the image resolution, particularly regarding image following conventional understanding": "",
  "Enhancing edges by subtracting a blurred version of the image (unsharp masking): A_sharp = A + alpha*(A - A_blur)": "",
  "Computing the SVD of the image, particularly regarding kernel in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "Unsharp masking adds back the high-frequency content: A_sharp = (1+alpha)*A - alpha*A_blur. The Laplacian kernel [[0,-1,0],[-1,4,-1],[0,-1,0]] directly detects and enhances edges through convolution.": "",
  "What is 'image segmentation' using spectral methods?": "",
  "Dividing an image into equal-sized rectangular blocks": "",
  "Partitioning an image into regions by using eigenvectors of a graph Laplacian constructed from pixel similarities": "",
  "Separating an image into its RGB channels": "",
  "Removing the background from an image": "",
  "Spectral segmentation builds a graph where pixels are nodes and edge weights represent similarity. The eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian (especially the Fiedler vector) reveal natural partitions of the image.": "",
  "What does 'image inpainting' refer to?": "",
  "Increasing the brightness of an image": "",
  "Painting new colors on top of an image": "",
  "Converting a photograph to a painting style": "",
  "Filling in missing or damaged regions of an image, often using low-rank matrix completion techniques": "",
  "Image inpainting reconstructs missing regions by exploiting structure in the image. Matrix completion methods assume the image has low-rank structure, using observed pixels to infer the missing ones.": "",
  "What is 'image registration' from a linear algebra perspective?": "",
  "Registering an image in a database": "",
  "Assigning each pixel to a class label": "",
  "Computing the histogram of an image": "",
  "Finding the affine transformation (rotation, translation, scaling) that best aligns two images": "",
  "Image registration finds a transformation matrix T that maps points in one image to corresponding points in another. The 2D affine transformation is a 2x3 matrix, and finding it involves solving a least-squares system.": "",
  "What is 'homography' in computer vision?": "",
  "A type of image filter, particularly regarding matrix when applying": "",
  "A graph of homogeneous coordinates when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "A rotation by exactly 180 degrees under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "A projective transformation represented by a 3x3 matrix that maps one planar image to another": "",
  "A homography H is a 3x3 matrix (up to scale) that maps points between two views of a planar surface using homogeneous coordinates: x' ~ Hx. It encompasses rotations, translations, scaling, and perspective distortions.": "",
  "What is 'total variation' denoising?": "",
  "A method that only works for black and white images": "",
  "Removing all variation from the image to make it uniform": "",
  "A denoising method that minimizes the sum of gradient magnitudes across the image while staying close to the noisy input": "",
  "Computing the variance of all pixel values": "",
  "Total variation (TV) denoising minimizes ||grad(u)||_1 + lambda||u - f||^2 where f is the noisy image. The L1 gradient penalty preserves edges while removing noise, making it superior to simple smoothing.": "",
  "What is 'morphological image processing' and how does it relate to matrix operations?": "",
  "Computing eigenvalues of the image matrix": "",
  "Applying the Fourier transform to change image shape": "",
  "Converting between different image file formats": "",
  "Operations like erosion and dilation that use min/max operations with a structuring element, forming a nonlinear alternative to convolution": "",
  "Morphological operations use min (erosion) and max (dilation) instead of weighted sums. While not strictly linear, they can be expressed using matrix-like operations with a structuring element acting like a kernel.": "",
  "A photographer wants to compress a 2000x3000 photo using rank-50 SVD. What compression ratio does she achieve (comparing stored values)?": "",
  "About 5:1": "",
  "About 24:1": "",
  "About 50:1": "",
  "About 100:1": "",
  "Original: 2000 * 3000 = 6,000,000 values. Rank-50 SVD: 2000*50 + 50 + 3000*50 = 100,000 + 50 + 150,000 = 250,050 values. Ratio: 6,000,000 / 250,050 ~ 24:1.": "",
  "A medical imaging researcher applies the 3x3 Laplacian kernel [[0,-1,0],[-1,4,-1],[0,-1,0]] to detect tumors in an MRI scan. What does this kernel detect?": "",
  "Smooth regions with constant intensity": "",
  "The average intensity of the image": "",
  "Color gradients only": "",
  "Edges and boundaries where pixel intensity changes rapidly": "",
  "The Laplacian kernel computes the second derivative of the image, which is zero in smooth regions and large at edges/boundaries. It highlights tumor boundaries where tissue density changes abruptly.": "",
  "A satellite imaging engineer applies a 2D affine transformation to correct geometric distortion. The transformation maps point (x, y) to (x', y') using the matrix equation [x', y']^T = [[a, b], [c, d]] * [x, y]^T + [e, f]^T. How many parameters must she estimate?": "",
  "4": "",
  "2": "",
  "9": "",
  "6": "",
  "A 2D affine transformation has 6 parameters: 4 in the linear part (a, b, c, d for rotation, scaling, shearing) and 2 in the translation (e, f). Three point correspondences provide 6 equations, enough to determine all parameters.": "",
  "A computer vision engineer builds a panorama by stitching 5 photos. She computes homography matrices between consecutive pairs. Each homography is a 3x3 matrix with 8 degrees of freedom (up to scale). How many point correspondences are needed between each pair?": "",
  "At least 1, particularly": "",
  "At least 4 (each gives 2 equations)": "",
  "At least 3, particularly": "",
  "At least 8, particularly": "",
  "A homography has 8 degrees of freedom (9 entries minus 1 for scale). Each point correspondence gives 2 equations (one for x', one for y'). So 4 correspondences give 8 equations, exactly enough. In practice, more are used with RANSAC.": "",
  "A facial recognition system represents each face as a vector and computes distances. If it stores 1000 face templates of dimension 128, how much memory (in number of floating-point values) is needed?": "",
  "16,384,000": "",
  "128,000": "",
  "128": "",
  "1,000": "",
  "Each face template is a 128-dimensional vector, and there are 1000 templates, so 1000 * 128 = 128,000 floating-point values are stored.": "",
  "A video surveillance system processes 30 frames per second of 1080p video (1920x1080). Each frame is a matrix. Background subtraction uses a low-rank model for the static background. What matrix decomposition separates foreground from background?": "",
  "Cholesky decomposition of each frame as predicted by standard models": "",
  "LU factorization of each frame, particularly regarding lambda as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Robust PCA: decompose the video matrix as L + S where L is low-rank (background) and S is sparse (foreground)": "",
  "QR factorization of the video, particularly regarding decomposition following the established framework": "",
  "Robust PCA decomposes the data matrix (frames as columns) into L (low-rank background that changes slowly) and S (sparse foreground of moving objects). This is solved by minimizing ||L||_* + lambda||S||_1.": "",
  "A graphics designer applies a color transformation matrix to convert an image from one color space to another. The transformation from RGB to YCbCr uses a 3x3 matrix. If the original pixel is (R, G, B) = (255, 0, 0) (pure red), the Y (luminance) component is approximately 0.299R + 0.587G + 0.114B. What is Y?": "",
  "About 76.2": "",
  "255": "",
  "About 150": "",
  "0": "",
  "Y = 0.299(255) + 0.587(0) + 0.114(0) = 76.245 ~ 76.2. The luminance weights reflect human visual sensitivity (most sensitive to green, least to blue).": "",
  "A computer vision researcher uses SIFT features, which represent local image patches as 128-dimensional vectors. To match features between two images, she computes the nearest neighbor using Euclidean distance. For 1000 features in each image, how many distance computations are needed for brute-force matching?": "",
  "1,000,000": "",
  "2,000": "",
  "Brute-force matching compares every feature in image 1 against every feature in image 2: 1000 * 1000 = 1,000,000 distance computations. This can be optimized using the matrix product X1 * X2^T for the cross-term in Euclidean distance.": "",
  "A deep learning researcher uses a convolutional neural network where the first layer has 32 filters of size 3x3 applied to a single-channel 28x28 image. How many parameters (excluding bias) are in this layer?": "",
  "896": "",
  "32": "",
  "288": "",
  "25,088": "",
  "Each filter is 3x3 = 9 parameters, and there are 32 filters: 32 * 9 = 288 parameters. The number of parameters depends on filter size and count, not the input image size.": "",
  "An autonomous vehicle system processes stereo camera images to estimate depth. The fundamental matrix F relates corresponding points between left and right images by x'^T F x = 0. What are the properties of the fundamental matrix?": "",
  "F is always the identity matrix": "",
  "F is a 3x3 matrix of rank 2 (singular) with 7 degrees of freedom": "",
  "F is a 3x3 orthogonal matrix": "",
  "F is a 2x2 positive definite matrix": "",
  "The fundamental matrix F is 3x3 with rank 2 (det(F) = 0). It has 9 entries, minus 1 for scale, minus 1 for the det=0 constraint = 7 degrees of freedom. At least 7 point correspondences are needed to estimate it.": ""
